"{\n  \"text\": \"Hi everybody, Scotty here at the Regenerative Agriculture Project in Neatville, Texas. And I read something interesting uh in uh Gabe Brown's book uh Dirt to Soil, which I highly recommend. I think it's great. But uh he was saying that uh when you add synthetic fertilizers to the ground, we all kind of know that that damages the microbial and the fungal communities that exist in the ground. It tends to burn them a little bit, but also that it disrupts the plant's ability to communicate with those microbes. The microbes deliver nutrients to the plant, and in exchange the plant delivers or uh exudates uh carbon back into the soil. And what happens is that the plant apparently sends a signal to the microbes, and the microbes respond by bringing the necessary nutrients that the plant calls out for it. But when you add synthetic scent fertilizers, the plants stop doing that. They they kind of lose their ability to communicate with the microbes. They they learn how to speak microbes. Anyway, I thought that was fascinating. I wanted to share it. Thanks, y'all.\",\n  \"sentences\": [\n    {\n      \"text\": \" Hi everybody, Scotty here at the Regenerative Agriculture Project in Neatville, Texas.\",\n      \"start\": 0.4,\n      \"end\": 5.2,\n      \"duration\": 4.8,\n      \"confidence\": 0.99,\n      \"tokens\": [\n        {\n          \"text\": \" Hi\",\n          \"start\": 0.4,\n          \"end\": 0.64,\n          \"duration\": 0.24,\n          \"confidence\": 0.994\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \" ever\",\n          \"start\": 0.72,\n          \"end\": 0.8,\n          \"duration\": 0.08,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"yb\",\n          \"start\": 0.8,\n          \"end\": 0.96,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"ody\",\n          \"start\": 0.96,\n          \"end\": 1.04,\n          \"duration\": 0.08,\n          \"confid